What is the difference between battery chemistry? Batteries in laptops and notebooks are primarily Lithium Ion (Li-Ion) or Lithium Polymer (Li-Pol) technologies. We carry both types of batteries, depending on your laptop model and type. Each type of rechargeable battery technology has its own unique characteristics: -Lithium Ion (Li-Ion) is the newest type of battery technology, which does not suffer from the "memory effect" at all. This means it is OK to recharge your battery at any time, even if it's not fully discharged. These batteries have twice the energy older battery technologies, while weighing less. This is especially helpful for portable electronics, such as laptops and digital cameras. -Lithium Polymer (Li-Pol) is very similar to Li-Ion; however cells are constructed of a different material. Flat polymer sheets are used to make flat batteries. This allows batteries to be placed in small places like behind laptop screens. This technology is only used in limited laptop applications; however it is more widely used in PDAs, tablet computers, and cell phones. Polymer technology is commonly used in newer Apple laptops. Back to top What is capacity (mAh) and difference in cell count? The capacity of our batteries is rated in mAh (Milli-Amp Hours). If the capacity of a battery is 4400mAh, it means that this battery can deliver 4400 Milli-Amps of current for 1 hour at the rated voltage. The actual amount of power a laptop uses depends on the usage. Many things can affect how much power is used, such as LCD screen brightness, CPU usage, video card usage, and internet usage. More demanding applications and video playback drain more power, as compared to simple applications such as word processing and e-mail. For many laptop models, we offer higher capacity models for those individuals who use their laptops off the charger for extended periods of time. This is common with businessmen and women who travel often, and students who use their laptops in the classroom and study areas. Higher capacity models will require more internal battery cells. This means that although the battery is designed to fit into your battery slot perfectly, it may protrude on the back side 1/2 inch to 1 inch to accommodate the additional cells. This will often result in a slightly raised typing surface, much like extending the legs on the back of a keyboard. Back to top What are Volts and Amps? A voltage rating is an evaluation based on research and experimentation that help determine how much voltage can be safely utilized by a particular device or form of wiring over the life of the device or wiring. For electrical and electronic devices, this rating is determined during product development and testing by increasing the voltage levels until the devices break down or begin malfunctioning. The voltage of the new battery should always match the voltage of your original (about +/- 1 Volt is OK). Some of our batteries will have higher mAh than the original battery found in your device. This is indicative of a longer run-time (higher capacity) and will not cause any incompatibilities. Back to top Does the voltage of the new battery need to match the voltage of my original battery? While the new battery voltage may not be identical to the original battery, the voltages must be within a reasonable range. While manufacturers strive to keep the voltage consistent with original equipment, sometimes there may be a small variation. This difference is usually +/- 1 volt, and will not affect the performance of the battery. A Li-Ion battery labeled 10.8V will function the same as a Li-Ion battery labeled 11.1V. A Li-Ion battery labeled 14.4V will function the same as a Li-Ion battery labeled 14.8V. Back to top How should I care for my new rechargeable laptop battery? Refer to the pamphlet included with your new battery for initial installation instructions. Upon initial use (or after a prolonged storage period) the battery may require three to four charge/discharge cycles before achieving maximum capacity. When charging the battery for the first time your computer may indicate that charging is complete after just a few minutes. This is a normal occurrence with new rechargeable batteries. Unfortunately, this does not mean the battery is fully charged. If this happens, simply remove the battery from the computer and repeat the charging process. It is important to cycle (fully discharge and then fully charge) the battery every two to three weeks. Not doing so may significantly shorten the battery's life. To discharge, simply run your device under the battery's power until it shuts down or until you get a low battery alert (a simple way to do this quickly would be to stream movie clips online, or play a DVD). Then recharge the battery as instructed. If the battery will not be in use for a month or longer, it is recommended that the battery be fully charged and removed from the device and stored in a cool, dry, clean place. It is normal for a battery to become warm during charging and discharging. A charged battery will eventually lose its charge if unused. It may therefore be necessary to recharge the battery after a storage period. Back to top Will installing your battery void my original manufacturer warranty? This is a common misconception as most manufacturers want you to purchase their original branded batteries, which are often overpriced. Purchasing a high quality replacement from LB1 High Performance is an affordable & cost-effective alternative. Batteries from LB1 High Performance are manufactured to the same exacting specifications as original equipment costing two or three times as much. Federal law (15 USC Chapter 50 - Consumer Product Warranties) prohibits manufacturers from this type of practice. In short, the answer is NO - our products WILL NOT void your original manufacturer warranty. All our high quality batteries are guaranteed to meet and/or exceed original equipment specifications. We stand behind the quality of our products with a money-back guarantee and $100,000 equipment protection plan. Back to top What if I need a return or exchange? We understand that sometimes there may be instances where you may require a return or exchange. We offer a 30-day return or exchange policy. It is clearly stated on our listings that buyers are responsible for return shipping, unless it is a shipping error on our behalf. To begin a return or exchange, please visit your "My eBay" page and go to you purchase history, and then locate the item which you purchased from us. There will be a drop-down menu that says "More Actions" - please select "Return This Item" to begin the return/exchange process. There will be step-by-step instructions to guide you. If you have any questions, call or send a message to our customer service department and we will be glad to assist you. Back to top What is the difference between your battery and an original (OEM) battery? Basically, there is no difference between our battery and the one that originally came with your laptop - with the exception of the brand name stamp. Our batteries are manufactured to the same exacting specifications as the original battery, and they are guaranteed to meet or exceed those specifications. With a LB1 High Performance High Performance laptop battery, you will get the same performance and quality of an original battery at only a fraction of the cost. Back to top How long does a new laptop battery last? The life of a rechargeable battery operating under normal conditions is generally between 300 to 400 charge-discharge cycles. This roughly translates into 1.5 to 2 years of battery life under average use. As your rechargeable battery begins to die, you will notice a decline in the running time of the battery. When your battery is only providing you with an hour or less or runtime, it needs to be replaced. Back to top What if my new battery is not charging? Due to shipping regulations, brand new batteries are typically shipped in a discharged or low capacity condition. We generally recommend a fully charge the first time using. Refer to the pamphlet included with your battery for charging instructions. Rechargeable batteries should be cycled - fully charged and then fully discharged 2 to 4 times initially to allow them to reach their full capacity. Sometimes your laptop will stop charging a new battery before it is fully charged. If this happens, simply remove the battery from your device and then re-insert it. The charge cycle should begin again. This may happen several times during your first battery charge - this is normal behavior for a new battery. If you have followed all instructions and your laptop is still not charging or recognizing the battery, you may need a BIOS update. Your computer's BIOS (Basic Input/Output System) is the first software your PC loads. It sets the stage for your operating system; so to speak, by finding all your PC's various hardware components and letting the operating system know it can use them. On most laptop manufacturer's websites, there will be an area to download the newest BIOS. Back to top What If I can't find my exact battery? To be cost-effective, laptop manufacturers designed their batteries and AC adapters to be compatible with many of their models. A single battery or adapter can be compatible with up with 1000+ different models! While we do our best to maintain the most up-to-date compatibility list, it is not possible for us to collect and post all the model numbers at one time. If you can match your battery visually to our listed battery, but it is not listed under compatible part/model number, please contact us and one of our expert representatives will be happy to assist you. Many times, we can double-check for you and confirm if your laptop is compatible. If we do not currently carry your battery or adapter, we will make every effort to add it to our always-expanding inventory catalog in the future. Back to top What if the image matches my battery/adapter, but it is a different model number? One battery or adapter can be compatible with anywhere from 10-1000 different models. Generally all models in a particular series will use the same battery and AC adapter. For example: HP DV6-1000ET, HP DV6-1001TX, HP DV6-1099EF all use the same battery. Dell Inspiron M5010, Dell Inspiron M5030, Inspiron M5030D all use the same battery. If your battery matches up physically to the image and specifications, but the listing is for a different model, please contact us to verify before making the purchase. Return shipping for incorrect orders will have to be paid by the buyer. Back to top My laptop shows my battery is fully charged, but it is not working. It helps to think of a new battery as a new pair of shoes, they need to be broken in. New batteries are usually shipped in a discharged state and need to be fully charged before use. For this reason, new batteries can be challenging. Your initial charge should take several hours. If your new batteries indicate they are fully charged within a few minutes or less than an hour you may have a condition known as "False Peak". This is a condition where the battery gives a false reading of being fully charged. If this happens, simply remove the battery from the charger and put it back in again. You may need to do this several times until the battery finally begins to accept a charge. Once a new battery has been charged it still may not last as long as you think it should. Don?t panic. Sometimes a battery needs to be charged and discharged a few times to reach its full capacity. Back to top What is the run time of the battery? Exact battery runtime on a laptop is difficult to determine. Actual battery runtime depends upon the specific power demands of your machine. The brightness of the screen, hard drive usage, graphics card usage, and USB usage results in an additional drain upon the battery, effectively reducing its run time. Usually, our new batteries will run as long as, or up to 25% to 50% longer than your old battery did when it was new. Back to top How can I maximize my laptop battery performance? There are several steps you can take to insure that you get maximum performance and life from your battery. Here are some tips from PCWorld magazine: -Plug in whenever possible: One surefire way to ensure that your laptop is always ready for action is to plug it into an AC outlet whenever possible. Keeping the machine fully charged makes it far more likely that you will always have the juice you need to complete your work. Purchase at least one extra AC adapter, so you?ll always have one in your office and one in your laptop bag for travel. If you work at home frequently, consider buying a third adapter to leave there. If you can, it also helps to have an extra battery in your laptop bag so you can save and resume working when you don't have access to an outlet nearby. -Adjust the screen brightness: Modern displays with LED backlights are a major improvement over the CCFL (cold cathode fluorescent tube) backlit displays of yesteryear, in terms of both picture quality and power efficiency. Still, a laptop?s display claims a significant percentage of the power that the system consumes. As such, keeping the screen backlight low can increase your laptop?s run time noticeably. You should also take care in choosing where you work: A low backlight setting will be far more comfortable in a café with soft lighting than in a brightly lit room. -Track down errant apps: One culprit often responsible for draining the battery ahead of its time is the presence of errant software applications that suck up disproportionate processor cycles. Unnecessary utilities running in the background, or an app that is hanging, can also cause this effect. Web browsers are particularly prone to the latter problem, due to the multiple plug-ins, rendering engines, and scripting engines embedded within them. Modern CPUs save power by dynamically scaling back their clock speed to the minimum possible, but they can do so only when apps aren?t active. If you fail to deal with rogue apps, they will not only drain battery power?they might also slow down your entire system. One clue to the existence of an errant app is if your laptop fan frequently kicks into high gear when the machine should be idle. Resolving the problem is relatively straightforward: Press the Ctrl-Alt-Delete key combination, launch Windows Task Manager, and use it to identify processes that are showing unexplained high utilization. If a program won?t exit normally, terminate the offending process by right-clicking it and selecting Kill Process. For Web browsers, shutting off all instances usually works. Should all else fail, perform a system restart. -Disable intensive background apps: Errant apps aside, applications that make intensive use of the processor or network should remain closed when your laptop isn?t plugged in. Peer-to-peer software such as BitTorrent clients and computationally intensive applications such as distributed-computing projects are out. You can also confirm that Windows Update and other software updaters are not attempting to download large software patches. Disabling automatic Windows Update functions outright is too draconian (particularly if you forget to reinstate the feature later), but periodically checking on your network usage for unexplained spikes will allow you to identify and stop large file transfers before they gobble up precious minutes of battery life. -Disable unneeded devices: You can disable unneeded hardware devices or ports to squeeze out a few more minutes of power, although this option isn?t possible with every laptop. Start by disabling unneeded wireless capabilities, such as built-in data modems and Wi-Fi and Bluetooth radios (many laptops have hardware switches for this purpose). The optical-disc drive is another power guzzler that can drain batteries fast, so don?t leave a DVD or Blu-ray disc in the drive if you don?t need it. Finally, many laptops these days come with backlit keyboards; these are great when you?re in a dark environment, but you can save precious power by doing without the feature when your laptop is running on battery power. All our batteries are brand new. We DO NOT sell refurbished batteries. Refurbished batteries are used batteries. Some laptop battery vendors offer refurbished discount laptop batteries for sale. Refurbished batteries are generally cheap & low-quality products that are sold at a fraction of the cost. The process of refurbishing a laptop battery costs more than manufacturing a new one. These "refurbished" laptop batteries are simply used laptop batteries that have been pulled from older laptops. It is impossible to know how much life is left in these old batteries. For that reason, those sellers will only include a warranty for a few months. We provide a standard 12-month warranty on all our batteries. Save yourself the trouble and purchase a brand new high-quality laptop battery from LB1 High Performance. Back to top How should I dispose my old battery, should I recycle it? Yes, you should definitely recycle your old laptop battery. Please be environmentally conscious and do not throw your old battery in the trash. Many local electronics stores such as Best Buy accept old batteries for recycling. Please call to ask. You can also visit http://www.call2recycle.org/ to find the nearest drop-off location to recycle your battery.
